string.text:
We are well aware of the main damaging factors of modern combat:
- ballistic – 75-90% (including small fragments of shells, mines and grenades – up to 80%);
- thermal (when exposed to open flame and flammable mixtures) – 1.4-2.3%;
- dynamic (under the influence of a shock wave) – 4.2-4.9%.
The overall incidence of limb injuries is 56-67%, with a fatal outcome occurring in 6-12% of cases.
At the same time, in most armies of the world, personal armor protection is traditionally represented only by a helmet and a bulletproof vest; their total area of protection does not exceed 30-35% of the body surface area, while the limbs and face of a soldier remain unprotected. Thus, even the United States, which has become experienced in local military conflicts around the world, only in 2011, having assessed the results of military operations in recent years, began to equip its troops with separate anti-fragmentation elements for limb protection.
Against this background, the Russian combat protective kit (BZK) "Permyachka" looks quite worthy, for the first time in world practice providing comprehensive protection for a serviceman. BZK has no analogues either in Russia or abroad, has a wide range of service and operational properties. The total area of protection of the kit is three times greater than the area of existing general-purpose personal armor protection means in the world.
The kit provides all-round protection for combat personnel from low-speed shell fragments, mines and grenades, protection from open flames, atmospheric influences and mechanical damage, protection of vital organs from damage by high-speed fragmentation elements, rifle and machine gun bullets.
The main parameters of the kit are as follows:
- all-round protection against shrapnel damage over an area of 180-220 sq. dm, including the extremities, eyes and face, against shrapnel at the level of the SS-68 steel helmet, as well as against exposure to open flame for at least 15 seconds;
- protection of at least 90% of the area of vital organs in the frontal and dorsal projections from high-speed fragments and bladed weapons;
- protection against bullets from AK74, AKM assault rifles, SVD, M16A1, M16A2 rifles and behind-the-armor contusion trauma (in combination with bulletproof armor blocks of a bulletproof vest);
- reducing the cutting effect of cold weapons in the forearm area;
- shockproof protection in the areas of the coccyx, femur, shoulder and elbow joints.
The life support elements of the BZK provide protection for the serviceman from adverse environmental conditions, transportation of combat equipment elements, help to overcome water obstacles, and provide camouflage in summer and winter conditions.
The product has been in service with the Russian Army since 2004.
The use of the BZK in combat conditions allows for a significant reduction in personnel losses and an increase in the combat capabilities of units.
Thus, the use of combat protective equipment during counter-terrorist operations in the North Caucasus has already saved the lives and health of many servicemen of the Russian army.
The result of further work to improve the protective and operational capabilities of the Permyachka combat protection kit was the modernized Permyachka-M combat protection kit, the composition of which was expanded by a number of additional unique elements.

Ratnik is a Russian combat gear for a serviceman, also called the "future soldier kit". "Ratnik" is part of a general project to improve the quality of an individual soldier on the battlefield by using the latest scientific achievements in navigation, night vision systems, monitoring the psychophysiological state of a soldier, and using advanced materials in the manufacture of armor and clothing fabrics. The system is a complex of modern means of protection, communications, weapons, and ammunition. Research and development work was carried out by dozens of Russian defense enterprises such as the Federal State Unitary Enterprise. According to the creators, the new equipment will be able to compete on equal terms with similar models of "future soldier" equipment. The "Ratnik" includes about 10 subsystems. According to the first deputy chairman of the Military-Industrial Commission created under the Government of the Russian Federation, Yuri Borisov, this kit will have a modular layout and will be adapted for action in a variety of conditions and at any time of day. "Ratnik" was developed on the basis of "Barmitsa" equipment.
The equipment was first presented to the public at the MAKS air show. Troop tests were conducted in December 2012 at the base of the 27th separate motorized rifle brigade in Alabino near Moscow. Following the results of the troop tests, the equipment elements received a positive assessment from the military command. The Ratnik includes several dozen weapon elements, including:
Aramid overalls made from Alutex fiber are capable of withstanding the impact of grenade, mine or shell fragments, and also have a certain fire resistance;
The protection kit includes a 6B43 bulletproof vest (with ceramic plates) of protection class 6a in an extended configuration (weight up to 15 kg) or class 5 in a standard configuration (weight up to 9 kg) according to GOST R 51136-98, GOST R 51112-97, GOST R 50941-96. And a multilayer helmet that can withstand a pistol bullet (protection class 1) from a distance of 5-10 m.
the kit is equipped with the Strelets control system, which includes means of communication, target designation, processing and display of information, and identification, allowing information about the soldier’s location to be transmitted to the command post;
a communicator that determines the coordinates of a fighter using GLONASS and GPS, to solve the problem of orientation on the ground and target designation and other applied calculations;
energy supply kits;
protective glasses capable of withstanding impacts from 6 mm fragments flying at a speed of 350 m/s;
knee and elbow pads;
water purification filters, autonomous heat sources;
AK-12 or other modernized AK versions, equipped with a night vision sight and a thermal imaging aiming system;
a video module for shooting from cover, consisting of a helmet-mounted mini-monitor and a television sight;
collimator sight "Krechet" and other devices (in addition to the sight, a 3x magnification spotting scope or a night vision monocular "Lun" can be installed);
The life support system includes backpacks of various types (a universal backpack with a capacity of 50 liters, a raid backpack with a capacity of 10 liters; an unloading vest with interchangeable quick-release elements), camouflage kits, a folding heat-insulating lining, a removable insulation for use in winter, a ventilated T-shirt, a vest with compartments for ammunition, a mat, a raincoat, a cap, a balaclava, and a mosquito net;
tent, sleeping bag;
active headphones that allow you to communicate during combat;
knife "Bumblebee".
The total weight of the set is up to 20 kilograms with a 6A protection class bulletproof vest. In the standard version, the weight will be up to 14 kilograms with a 5th class bulletproof vest. The weight of the helmet is 1.056 kg. In general, 90% of the soldier's body surface is covered. The bulletproof vest has several varieties from light to heavy with insert plates. The marine version of the bulletproof vest also has the properties of a life jacket, which makes it possible to stay afloat with it. Modularity allows you to attach any pockets to the unloading vest. The winter version will differ only in the presence of heat supply and insulation. The design assumes continuous wearing for at least 48 hours. Video information is transmitted from the sight to the eye indicator wirelessly. The communication system will allow the soldier to communicate with the command and colleagues at the tactical level. The saturation with electronics makes the soldier a single combat system controlled by the latest technology. At the same time, information about the soldier's location is transmitted to the command post (CP), which greatly reduces the likelihood of being lost without a trace. Communication is provided by the Strelets reconnaissance, control and communications system, which allows exchanging information via voice or text messages, target designation, and photo and video shooting. The television sight on the machine gun provides an image in the eyecup, which allows shooting and observation from cover or from the hip. Automatic control of anti-aircraft missile systems has been created for anti-aircraft gunners, with the help of which the commander detects targets at a distance of several tens of kilometers and transmits coordinates automatically to the soldiers. Up to nine anti-aircraft gunners can receive commands from one point. This will eliminate the need for the anti-aircraft gunners to visually search for targets themselves. The system allows you to leave an ambush at the right moment to shoot and hide again. It can also be used by snipers and grenade launchers to direct fire. Such a system can be used to protect military convoys.
Upon completion of service, worn clothing will be given to new recruits after sanitization.
